//-
  Pug supports two primary methods of iteration: each and while.
  Pugâ€™s first-class iteration syntax makes it easier to iterate over arrays
  and objects in a template:

ul
  each val in [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
    li= val

//-
  <ul>
  <li>1</li>
  <li>2</li>
  <li>3</li>
  <li>4</li>
  <li>5</li>
  </ul>

//- Pug also lets you iterate over the keys in an object:
  ul
    each val, index in {1:'one',2:'two',3:'three'}
      li= index + ': ' + val
//-
  <ul>
    <li>1: one</li>
    <li>2: two</li>
    <li>3: three</li>
  </ul>

//-
  The object or array to iterate over is just plain JavaScript.
  So, it can be a variable, or the result of a function call, or almost anything else.

- var values = [];
ul
  each val in values.length ? values : ['There are no values']
    li= val

//-
  <ul>
    <li>There are no values</li>
  </ul>


//-
  One can also add an else block that will be executed if the array or object does
  not contain values to iterate over. The following is equivalent to the example above:
- var values = [];
ul
  each val in values
    li= val
  else
    li There are no values

//-
  <ul>
    <li>There are no values</li>
  </ul>
